# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grammar-of-graphics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] On 2 March 2012, ggplot2 version 0.9.0 was released with numerous changes to internal organization, scale construction and layers.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] On 25 February 2014, Hadley Wickham formally announced that "ggplot2 is shifting to maintenance mode.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] This means that we are no longer adding new features, but we will continue to fix major bugs, and consider new features submitted as pull requests.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] In recognition [of] this significant milestone, the next version of ggplot2 will be 1.0.0".
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] In the announcement, it was stated that "ggplot2 now has an official extension mechanism.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] On 5 July 2018, ggplot2 3.0.0 was released (initially planned as a ggplot2 2.3.0).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] This now provides support for tidy evaluation allowing quasiquotation in ggplot2 functions.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] In contrast to base R graphics, ggplot2 allows the user to add, remove or alter components in a plot at a high level of abstraction.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] This abstraction comes at a cost, with ggplot2 being slower than lattice graphics.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] Creating separate plots for various subsets of data in base R requires loops and manual management, whereas ggplot2 simplifies that process with a collection of "facet" functions to choose from.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] One potential limitation of base R graphics is the "pen-and-paper model" utilized to populate the plotting device.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] Graphical output from the interpreter is added directly to the plotting device or window, rather than separately for each distinct element of a plot.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] In this respect it is similar to the lattice package, though Wickham argues ggplot2 inherits a more formal model of graphics from Wilkinson.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] As such, it allows for a high degree of modularity; the same underlying data can be transformed by many different scales or layers.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] Plots may be created via the convenience function `qplot()` where arguments and defaults are meant to be similar to base R's `plot()` function.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] More complex plotting capacity is available via `ggplot()` which exposes the user to more explicit elements of the grammar.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] Wickham posits the success of ggplot2 comes from the increased popularity of the R language and the relative ease of making aesthetically appealing graphics.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] Along with more serious uses of ggplot2, Wickham also supports the more unusual use cases, like exploring factors for winning in the reality TV show RuPaul's Drag Race.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/ggplot2] See implementations of The Grammar of Graphics.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] Jacques Bertin was born in 1918 in Maisons-Laffitte, Yvelines.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] When he was 10, he received the first prize of cartography at primary school.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] He never had problems with drawing, and pursued interests including architecture, the teaching of drawing and cartography.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] Finally he ended up studying geography and cartography at the Sorbonne.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] He became founder and director of the Cartographic Laboratory of the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in 1954 and director of studies (directeur d'études) in 1957.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] In 1967 he became professor of the Sorbonne, and in 1974 he became director of studies and director of the Geographical Laboratory of the École des hautes études en sciences sociales (EHESS), which is part of the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE, VIe Section).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] Later in the 1970s he became head of research at the Centre national de la recherche scientifique (CNRS).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] In 1993 Bertin received the "Mercator-Medaille der Deutschen Gesellschaft für Kartographie" and in 1999 the Carl Mannerfelt Gold Medal from the International Cartographic Association.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/jacques-bertin] Jacques Bertin has published numerous scientific maps, papers and articles on map making, semiology, graphical information and graphic processing.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] The **Grammar of Graphics** (GoG) is a grammar-based system for representing graphics to provide grammatical constraints on the composition of data and information visualizations.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] A graphical grammar differs from a graphics pipeline as it focuses on semantic components such as scales and guides, statistical functions, coordinate systems, marks and aesthetic attributes.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] For example, a bar chart can be converted into a pie chart by specifying a polar coordinate system without any other change in graphical specification.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] The grammar of graphics concept was launched by Leland Wilkinson in 2001 (Wilkinson et al., 2001; Wilkinson, 2005) and graphical grammars have since been written in a variety of languages with various parameterisations and extensions.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] The grammar of graphics continues to evolve with alternate parameterisations, extensions, or new specifications.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] This computational system is not a taxonomy of charts and rather it describes the meaning of what we do when we construct statistical graphics.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Wilkinson wrote SYSTAT, a statistical software package, in the early 1980s.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] This program was noted for its comprehensive graphics, including the first software implementation of the heatmap display now widely used among biologists.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] After his company grew to 50 employees, he sold it to SPSS in 1995.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] At SPSS, he assembled a team of graphics programmers who developed the nViZn platform that produces the visualizations in SPSS, Clementine, and other analytics products.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] While at Stanford, Tableau founders Hanrahan and Stolte, as well as Diane Tang, created the predecessor to Tableau, named Polaris.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Polaris was a data visualization software tool, built with the support of a United States Department of Energy defense program, the Accelerated Strategic Computing Initiative (ASCI).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] The main differences between Wilkinson's system and Polaris are the use of SQL relational algebra for database services and using shelves instead of cross and nest operators.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Hadley Wickham conceived an alternate parameterisation of the syntax Wilkinson had derived, creating a layered grammar of graphics which he implemented as ggplot2 for R (programming language) users.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] This added a hierarchy of defaults based around the idea of building up a graphic from multiple layers.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Wilkinson is generally positive on Wickham's parameterisation and implementation of ggplot2, praising its elegance and expressivity whilst claiming that his original Grammar of Graphics is capable of representing a wider range of statistical graphics.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] ggplot2 is the first implementation of a layered grammar of graphics in R and implementations in other programming languages have ensued.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] These include direct ports plotnine for Python, gramm for MATLAB, Lets-Plot for Kotlin and gadfly for Julia.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Projects inspired by elements of Wickham's grammar include Vega-Lite which specifies plots in JSON and uses a JavaScript engine.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Implementations for Python include Vega-Altair (built on top of Vega-Lite).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Vega-Lite combines ideas from Wilkinson's Grammar of Graphics and Wickham's Layered Grammar of Graphics with a composition algebra for layered and multi-view displays with a grammar of interaction.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] The Vega-Lite specification is instantiated in JSON and rendered by the lower-level Vega.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/the-grammar-of-graphics] Whilst Vega-Lite is the sole implementation of this graphics grammar specification with compilation to Vega, other implementations do create JSON files which can be interpreted by Vega-Lite.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:grammar-of-graphics/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
